<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO ARTHUR AND OTHERS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Sep 24 23:57:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur, the demon in you is yours to stop. And you can. Seek the company of fellow vets, be it at the local V.A. Hospital Outpatient Psych, or some other faciity. Talking it out with brothers and sisters is the key.  The mind is a strange creature, it captures and holds, creates and manigifies,<br>
distorts and changes, the orignial event.  Nam was bad enough, you don't need to embelish it, change it, make it worse. Let it go. Easy for me to say, impossible for you to do, I know.  But with the help of others you can.<br><br>
You are not the sole owner of the demon, many other vets have it too.  They can let it go and so can you. F*** this talk about fear and control. That does little good in the middle of the night.  Let it go man.  Let it go and see that it has no grip on you afterall.  You won't go insane, you won't go crazy, even though you think you will, that is the hidden secred of PTSD. That you are crazy or will go crazy if you acknowledge, talk about, or share what is happening to you.  It is a bullshit secret. It is wrong.<br><br>
Yell it from the roof top. Scream it down the the street. You earned the right. PTSD is real, but you can tune down the intensity by not yielding to the MYTH of the power of it. It has NO POWER, NONE.  It is just in your head, and you can stop it.  You ain't nuts just because you think you are.<br>
Let it go Art, you don't need it and it don't need you.  Come on up for air. It gets cold and scary below the surface, but with the light of day, and the air above, even the divers know the the sweetness of the day.  So can you.
<p><code>-- sorry, I sort of hung out my shingle...  (doc spatz) </code><p>


